Paragraph: (1) "Take it and put it in the cupboard, for you will need it some day.". (2) Heidi obeyed, and danced around the hut in her delight to see all the beloved thingsagain. (3) Running up to the loft, she exclaimed in great disappointment: "Oh grandfather, my bed is gone.". (4) "It will come again," the grandfather called up from below; "how could I know that you were coming back? (5) Get your milk now!". (6) Heidi, coming down, took her old seat. (7) She seized her bowl and emptied it eagerly, as if it was the most wonderful thing she had ever tasted. (8) "Grandfather, our milk is the best in all the world.". (9) Suddenly Heidi, hearing a shrill whistle, rushed outside, as Peter and all his goats came racing down. (10) Heidi greeted the boy, who stopped, rooted to the spot, staring at her. (11) Then she ran into the midst of her beloved friends, who had not forgotten her either. (12) Schwänli and Bärli bleated for joy, and all her other favorites pressed near to her. (13) Heidi was beside herself with joy, and caressed little Snowhopper and patted Thistlefinch, till she felt herself pushed to and fro among them. (14) "Peter, why don't you come down and say good-night to me?". (15) Heidi called to the boy. (16) "Have you come again?". (17) he exclaimed at last. (18) Then he took Heidi's proffered hand and asked her, as if she had been always there: "Are you coming up with me to-morrow?". (19) "No, to-morrow I must go to grandmother, but perhaps the day after.". (20) Peter had a hard time with his goats that day, for they would not follow him. (21) Over and over again they came back to Heidi, till she entered the shed with Bärli and Schwänli and shut the door. (22) When Heidi went up to her loft to sleep, she found a fresh, fragrant bed waiting for her; and she slept better that night than she had for many, many months, for her great and burning longing had been satisfied. (23) About ten times that night the grandfather rose from his couch to listen to Heidi's quiet breathing. (24) The window was filled up with hay, for from now on the moon was not allowed to shine on Heidi any more. (25) But Heidi slept quietly, for she had seen the flaming mountains and had heard the fir-trees roar.



