Paragraph: (1) Some of the sights I saw there, where a horse had to come downhill with a heavily loaded two-wheel cart behind him, on which no brake could be placed, make me sad even now to think of. (2) After Rory was disabled I often went in the carriage with a mare named Peggy, who stood in the next stall to mine. (3) She was a strong, well-made animal, of a bright dun color, beautifully dappled, and with a dark-brown mane and tail. (4) There was no high breeding about her, but she was very pretty and remarkably sweet-tempered and willing. (5) Still, there was an anxious look about her eye, by which I knew that she had some trouble. (6) The first time we went out together I thought she had a very odd pace; she seemed to go partly a trot, partly a canter, three or four paces, and then a little jump forward. (7) It was very unpleasant for any horse who pulled with her, and made me quite fidgety. (8) When we got home I asked her what made her go in that odd, awkward way. (9) “Ah,” she said in a troubled manner, “I know my paces are very bad, but what can I do? (10) It really is not my fault; it is just because my legs are so short. (11) I stand nearly as high as you, but your legs are a good three inches longer above your knee than mine, and of course you can take a much longer step and go much faster. (12) You see I did not make myself. (13) I wish I could have done so; I would have had long legs then. (14) All my troubles come from my short legs,” said Peggy, in a desponding tone. (15) “But how is it,” I said, “when you are so strong and good-tempered and willing?”



“Why, you see,” said she, “men will go so fast, and if one can't keep up to other horses it is nothing but whip, whip, whip, all the time. (16) And so I have had to keep up as I could, and have got into this ugly shuffling pace. (17) It was not always so; when I lived with my first master I always went a good regular trot, but then he was not in such a hurry. (18) He was a young clergyman in the country, and a good, kind master he was. (19) He had two churches a good way apart, and a great deal of work, but he never scolded or whipped me for not going faster. (20) He was very fond of me. (21) I only wish I was with him now; but he had to leave and go to a large town, and then I was sold to a farmer. (22) “Some farmers, you know, are capital masters; but I think this one was a low sort of man. (23) He cared nothing about good horses or good driving; he only cared for going fast. (24) I went as fast as I could, but that would not do, and he was always whipping; so I got into this way of making a spring forward to keep up. (25) On market nights he used to stay very late at the inn, and then drive home at a gallop. (26) “One dark night he was galloping home as usual, when all of a sudden the wheel came against some great heavy thing in the road, and turned the gig over in a minute. (27) He was thrown out and his arm broken, and some of his ribs, I think.



